As we begin the month of April, the threat of severe weather increases. Our mayor, Warren Dell, has assembled a team of individuals to open our Elementary storm shelter in the event that there is a TORNADO WARNING. Here is how it will work: When there is a TORNADO WARNING in Eastern Garfield County the front doors of the Elementary school will be opened so that Garber residents can shelter in the Elementary storm shelter.

Thank you to Warren Dell and also thank you to our patrons for providing facilities that keep our students and community safe.

Garber Public Schools Release: March 12, 2020
Spring Break is upon us, and we hope that everyone will enjoy their time off. Our current plan is to see all of our students return on Monday, March 23rd as scheduled. However, due to the rapidly changing landscape caused by coronavirus concerns, we want everyone to be aware that Garber Public Schools does have a contingency plan in place.

The full GPS Plan for Temporary Education Solutions can be seen by following this link.
https://s3.amazonaws.com/scschoolfiles/1905/gps_temporary_education_solutions.pdf
Again, we have currently made no changes and hope to see everyone on Monday, March 23rd. We want to keep our community informed in the case of school closures while we work to keep our students best interests at the heart of our decisions.

post_text:
Our next teacher feature is Mrs. Hostetler! She has spent the last many years teaching 5th and 6th Grade, but has taught or coached at the Elementary, Jr. High, and High School levels.

Mrs. Hostetler is a graduate of Oklahoma State University, and has been teaching for 36 years - 13 here at Garber. She previously taught in Perry, Sumner, Billings, and at Union Elementary.

Outside of teaching, Mrs. Hostetler enjoys spending time with family and friends. She also gardens, fishes, and loves to check out antique shops!

Mrs. Hostetler has been married to her husband, Brady, for 37 years, and they farm and ranch near Billings. They have a daughter and son, who are both Garber Alumni, and a big German Shepherd named Radar!

We are excited to highlight Mrs. Hostetler today! Tune in after Christmas break as we feature the rest of our fantastic Teachers!

post_text: Garber’s Spanish I and II classes learned about the history of the piñata and how it became popular in Spanish speaking countries. We are so proud of their creations.

post_text:
Today’s Feature Teacher is Venus Sneary! Mrs. Sneary currently teaches JH Science, Keyboarding, and HS Earth Science, but has just about taught everything here at Garber!

Mrs. Sneary attended Phillips University and has been teaching for 22 years - all at Garber! She is also a Garber graduate.

In HS, her favorite subject was Vocational Agriculture. She enjoys spending time with family and taking family trips. She enjoys gardening and camping, and helping out with all FFA activities! She also enjoys helping Mr. Sneary farm and ranch.

We are thankful for Mrs. Sneary and her dedication to Garber Schools. There’s none quite like her!

Oops! We missed Tuesday! So here is our Feature Teacher (Thursday)!

Marilyn White is our Feature Teacher today! Mrs. White is currently our 4th Grade Teacher, but has taught 2nd, 5th, and 6th Grade as well.

Mrs. White graduated from Oklahoma State University and has been teaching for 43 years! 42 of those years have been at Garber, and she previously taught at Olive Public Schools.

Mrs. White’s favorite subjects are Reading and Social Studies. She loves the outdoors, gardening, and being a farm wife! We are extremely fortunate to have Mrs. White here at Garber - we’re sure a lot of you remember going to the one room schoolhouse with her.

Today’s Feature Teacher is Mrs. Sally Clickner! Mrs. Clickner currently teaches Desktop Publishing (Yearbook) and HS Computer.

Mrs. Clickner attended Northern Oklahoma College in Tonkawa and earned her Bachelor’s at Phillips University in Enid. She has taught for 44 years - all of them at Garber!

Mrs. Clickner’s favorite subjects were Business and History. She enjoys spending time and playing with her granddaughter. Outside of school she enjoys watching sporting events and gardening.

Mrs. Clickner’s grandfather attend Garber Public Schools starting in 1906 through the 10th Grade. She has enjoyed researching the history of the school the last several years as Garber has celebrated the first yearbook and the 100th graduating class!

post_text:
Garber Public Schools would like to share a little bit about each of our teachers, so we are starting Teacher Feature Tuesday.

Our first Feature Teacher of the week is Mrs. Nancy Nelson. Mrs. Nelson currently teaches Family & Consumer Sciences (8-12) and is a favorite among students.

Ms. Nelson attended Oklahoma State University (“Go Pokes!”) and earned her Bachelor’s Degree. She also did post graduate work at OSU. Mrs. Nelson has been teaching for 47 years, 44 of those years have been here at Garber!

Before coming to Garber, she taught at Morris. Mrs. Nelson’s favorite subject to teach is Clothing Construction. Her favorite subject in HS was Basketball and of course, Home Ec.

Outside of school, Ms. Nelson enjoys spending time with family and her animals, reading, sewing, woodworking, and gardening.

We are so fortunate to have Mrs. Nelson on our staff! She thinks that Garber has the best students and staff - “I’d put them up against ANY school in the USA!”

Here she is pictured on her “throne:”

Veteran's get in Free to this Friday's OSSAA Playoff Game
If you are a veteran, either active duty, retired, reserve or national guard, The OSSAA would like to invite you to attend the first round of the football playoffs for free next weekend! That’s right, all veterans and one guest will be admitted free of charge on Friday November 15th to all OSSAA first round football games. The OSSAA appreciates the sacrifices of all veterans, and hopes you will take advantage of this opportunity. Simply show your Military ID card, or driver’s license that shows your military status at the gate next Friday, and you and a guest will be omitted free of charge. See you next week, and thank you for your service!
